{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_himilco_ver01/data/sn84028262/00296026992/1920123101/0475.xml":{"full_text":"Medina, Ohio, Dec 31, 1920.\nr AGE TWO\nTHE MEDINA SENTINEL, MEDINA, OHIO.\nBRUNSWICK\nA Happy New Year to all.\nRemember the bake sale, spelling\nschool and watch meeting for Friday\nevening in the Methodist church.\nAlso the Odd Fellows' and Rebekahs'\noyster supper on Saturday night\nAlso the cantata at the Methodist\nchurch on Sunday evening\n4i thA Vnrmfirs' Institute in town\niuov vv mini hi ii. i q\nhall on Monday and Tuesday, Jan. d\nand 4.\nOn Thursday night of this week there\nis to be a school party in the town hall\nat which all former pupils are invited.\nThe next Grange meeting will be\nheld all day Jan. 15 in the town hall,\nat which time there will be the instal\nlation of the new officers.\nMrs. J. F. Babcock received word of\nthe birth of a little daugnier on uec.\n6 to Mrs. Cora Drake Bassett and\nhusband at Chicago.\nMrs. Jessie Peebles of Seville spent\nMonday here at Urant moseys aim\nMrs. T.vman Chidsey's.\nThe Y. M. C. A. boys met last week\nWednesday evening in the basement\nof Church of Christ and reorganized\nfor the year They will meet there\neach Wednesday evening.\nProf. Leland Drake, wife and daugh\nter of Ohio State, are spending their\nvacation here at his lather s.\nMrs. Ed. Fritz came home from\nCleveland to stay over Christmas with\nher family.\nM. A. Stoup, wife and daughter\nEleanor of Lester and Mrs. Leonard\nBart of Mallet Creek, were callers at\nE. C. Miner's on Christmas\nHarry Vaughn and family moved\ninto their new home, the Gardner\nplace ,this week, which they have re\nmodeled. Mrs. Forrest Tibbits was brought\nhome from a hospital in Cleveland on\nlast Friday. On Sunday she was ta\nken worse and an ambulance was call\ned and she was taken back, where, an\noperation was performed. She is\nnow improving.\nThe. Odd Fellows' received a letter\nfrom Dr. Wood stating that he had\ncommenced building their new home.\nHe wrote of the beautiful roses and\nhow they were getting ready for the\nannual rose carnival.\nRobert, a 10 1-2 pound boy, was\nbom Dec. 24 to Ernest Wilkey and\nwife. Mrs. Stella Sinzinger is car\ning for mother and baby.\n\"Fred Thompson and wife of Ritt\nman were callers at E. C. Miner's on\nMonday. They were at Valley Cty\non Sunday to attend the 38th wedding\nanniversary of his brother and wife.\nFor the corn display at Farmers In\nstitute, $20.00 will be given as prizes\nand $5.00 as sweepstakes, and it is\nurged you have your corn all there be\nfore noon of the first day.\nMrs Marie Craddock and two sons\nof Lorain spent the week-end at Ly\nman Pritchard's, and on Sunday morn\ning Mrs. Craddock sang a solo at the\nMethodist church, and her son Kieth,\naged 14 ,olayed a violin solo, with\nMargarette Stebbins as accompanist.\nMrs. Edith Darrah and son Paul of\nCleveland are spending the week here\nwith her mother, Mrs. Lyman Prit\nchard. Marian Perkm surprised her par\nents by coming home for the vacation\nfrom a school in Marysville, Tenn. Of\nthe 2,000 girls attending this school\nnine had decided to stay, but when the\nrest all left, these girls could not\nstand it and they left, too.\nJohn Randall and wife spent Chirst\nmas in Cleveland at their son's, and\nWhen either woman or man, husband or\nwife does business with us, we keep\nconfidential the amount of their deposit and\ntheir business transactions.\nWe advise every woman to have a bank\naccount of her own. It teaches her business\nmethods a very necessary thing for a\nwoman to know should she be left alone and\na helpful thing for her to know at all times.\nWe invite your banking business.\nThe Old Phoenix National Bank\nMEDINA, OHIO.\nthe grandson, Gordon, returned home\nwith them.\nPrimary and district schools will\ncommence on Jan. 3 and the high\nschool on Jan. 5.\nHINCKLEY\nMr. and Mrs. Charles Cady and\nson Curtis spent Christmus day at\nCharlie Veber's North Royalton.\nWill Rellus and wife received a\nbox of oranges from J. Parker, Ml.\nT til :jl\nuora, nuriuu.\nTlif. rV.WolmaB ovprriseifi at the Com\nmunity church were well attended.The\nchildren did well and the tree was\nwell filled with many useful pres\nents.\nThe W. B. A. will have installation\nof officers Jan. 8. Chicken pie din\nner, and all day meeting. All mem\nbers are requested to make an extra\neffort to be there.\nEli Shank is spending the winter\nwith Ms daughter, Mrs. L. Porter in\nWest Richfield.\nRaymond Charlton writes that at\npresent he is in Galveston, Texas.\nCorwin Riley came very near being\nseriously hurt when a bale of straw\nbeing put down in the barn struck\nhim in the face.\nThe Leslie Piero family spent\nChristmas day at xa. n. uiarnan s.\nThe Community Aid society will\nserve dinner at the Grange hall on\ni Jan. 6. Everybody come and get a\ngood dinner.\nMr. and Mrs. George McKee had for\ntheir guests on Christmas day Mr. and\nMrs. Horace McKee of Richfield, Mr.\nanrl Mis. Julian Riley and family and\nMr. and Mrs. Wallace McKee.\nStephen West and wife called all\ntheir children home to partake of a\nbountiful dinner on Christmas day.\nThere was a meeting Thursday night\nDec. 30 ,to make arrangements about\nputting in a furnace in the Community\nchurch. Let everyone take hold of\nthis as- it is badly needed.\nHinckley township Farm Bureau\nmet in Grange Hall on Wednesday af\nternoon, Dec. 22. There was a big\noyster feed with an attendance of\nabout 100. At the meeting there was\nelection of officers for the coming year.\nChairman, Fred Ellis; vice chairman,\nJ. E. Janoch; director, J. E. Janoch.\nExecutive Secretary Early of\nthe Countv Farm Bureau was present\nand gave a talk on the Indianapolis\nconvention: Mr. S. B. Stoddard was\nalso present and gave a strong talk\nytt the future of the Farm Bureau.\nGRANGERBURG\nMrs. Vida Hatch spent part of last\nweek in Uniontown visiting her sister,\nMrs. Snyder.\nCarl Graff and family and Lewis\nGraff and wife spent Xmas at Dr.\nI Cumberworth's.\nMr. and Mrs. Walter Young spent\nXmas at Ernest Young's.\nAlbert Indoe of Medina spent Xmas\nI with his parents, J. H. Indoe and wife,\nj Mrs. E. J. Haight is quite sick with\ntonsilitis.\nMr. and Mrs. Finley Anderson spent\ni Xmas at F. M. Hanson's.\nMr. O. G. Perrin and family spent\nXmas in Cleveland with Mrs. Perrin's\nparents; G. W. Ganyard with Mort\nCrane, in Wadsworth; Fred Webster\nand family and Owen Webster and\nfamily at Dr. Floyd Smith's in Cuya\nhoga Falls; Arthur Bagley and fami\nly at Rex Fryman's, in Stony Hill; E.\nR. Betzer's at Rev. Thompson's, and\nMilton Chester and wife, Viola Ches\nter and daughter, Lloyd Foote and\ndaughter,. Mrs. Hinman from School\nRoad, Brooklyn and Gilbert Hinman\nand famjly from Mallet Creek, at Vera\nRobinsons.\nOtis Pierce, who has been spending\nsome time with his uncle Ben, return\ned to his home in West Virginia last'\nweek.\nBuel Pierce is spending the holidays\nwith his brother Homer in Pennsyl\nvania.\nGeo. Ganyard went Monday to Louis\nville, Ky., to spend the remaining holi\ndays with a college friend.\nMrs. Chas. Gabriel is spending the\nweek with her parents, Mr. and Mrs.\nBen Pierce.\nAda Stein from Cleveland is visit\ning Josephine Lytle.\nDr. Reed and family spent Xmas\nin Weymouth at C. H. Scanlan's.\nMr. and Mrs. Chas. Ganyard and son\nGeorge, spent Xmas in Akron with WY\nH. Hammond and family.\nREMSON CORS.\nLawrence Dean and wife entertained\nher mother, Mrs. Linder of Bath, also\nPaul Jacot and family and Henry Lin\nder of Akron.\nMr. and Mrs. J. O. Crocker enter\ntained Will Huntley and wife of\nCleveland from Saturday until this\nweek Friday, also Ruth Crocker, who\nis attending school at Kent, is spend\ning her holiday vacation with her par\nents.\nMrs. Marv Beach and children, Cath\nerine and Gordon of Ashtabula, are\nvisiting relatives here.\nErnest Young and wife entertained\nBert Young and wife, Walter Young\nand wife, Mr. and Mrs. Harve Cutter,\nMr. and Mrs. Clair Halliwill and\nchildren of Richfield, and Mr. and Mrs.\nLoyd Betz and children of Medina on\nChristmas.\nFred Hanson and wife entertained\nthe following on Xmas: Mr. and Mrs.\nEarle Houck and son of Akron, Mr.\nand Mrs. Geo. Dunsha, Mr. and Mrs.\nHodd Dunsha, Mr. and Mrs. Loyd Han\nson of Columbus, Mr. and Mrs. Finley\nAnderson and daughter, Mr. and Mrs.\nDuane Baird and daughter, also Helen\nHanson and friend, Mr Stanley Cun\nningham and John Hanson and Mar\njorie Alber.\nMr. ad Mrs. Mel. Foskett and family\nof York spent Xmas at Grant Wel\nton's. Mr. and Mrs. B. C. Kimball spent\nXmas with their daughter and husband\nMr. and Mrs. Claude Woodward of\nCreston.\nWilliam Beardsley of Akron spent\nseveral days with his niece, Mrs. Chas.\nCase.\nSidney and Fanny Unick spent Xmas\nin Cleveland.\nThere will be an all-day meeting at\nthe church next Sunday. Reports of\nvarious organizations of the church\nwill be given and Rev. MoffeJ of Me\ndina will be the speaker. Paul Young\nof O. S. U. will lead the Christian En\ndeavor and will also be the speaker of\nthe evening.\nMrs. Agnes Woodward and husband\nof Creston spent Sunday with her par\nents, Mr. and Mrs. B. C. Kimball.\nMr. and Mrs. Clyde Keitt of Akron\nspent Xmas at Chas. Case's.\nMr. and Mrs. Glen Chapman enter\ntained his parents, Frank Chapman\nand wife, also Archie Chapman and\nwife, Xmas.\nPRETTIEST GIRL IN\nTREASURY DEPT.\nThe United .nates Treasury\nDepartment had to find its pret\ntiest girl recently to christen an\nimmense oil painting of President\nWilson. The vote cast was in\nfavor of Miss Betty Eader\nI Chevrolet \"FB 40\" Sedan 1\nDignity of design, every refinement of comfort and convenience, and certainty of service in all seasons ae w\nm cause for pride in this model. m\nj GIBBS CO. I\nj Medina, Oliio 1 I\nDWINDLING OF PASTURES\nAIDS LIVESTOCK DECLINE\nThat fee gradual decline of live\nstock in Ohio is due to the dwindling\nof pasture production is pointed out\nby Director Thome, of the Ohio Ex\nperiment Station.\nHe states that we must begin a sys\ntem of fertilization for pastures just\nthe same as for corn, wheat or oats.\nThis generally consists in applying\nlimestone, phosphate and manure as\na topdressing or to .provide for the\nfertilizing of pastures when other\nfarm crops are grown.\nThe Township assessors reports from\npractically every county in Ohio show\na steady decrease in the number of\ncattle kepi This means a lowering\nof the amount of manure produced on\nfarms.\nIt is believed that wheat production\nin Ohio has been seriously held up be\ncause of the lack of farm manures.\nThe acre production of wheat has in\ncreased very little during the past 50\nyears; in fact, it has been maintained\nby shifting to the land best adapted\nfor wheat and small use of commer.\ncial fertilizers.\nEven at this, Ohio will be consuming\nall the wheat it produces at the end\nof 5 years if the population continues\nto increase during that time.\nThere has been increase of a million\nacres of the area in paisture in Ohio\nsince the 'seventies in face of the de\ncrease equivalent to h&lf a million\ncattle in the number of livestock,\nshowing that the production of pas\ntures has heavily diminished.\nOBITUARY\nAnna Koppes Lee, youngest of the\nfamily of Abram and Nancy Koppes,\nwas born in Wadsworth township, oh\nDec. '9, 1843, and departed this life\nDec. 5, 1920, aged five days less than\nseventy-seven years.\nOn March 9, 1871, she was married\nto William A. Lee, a teacher in the\nschools of Guilford township, where\nafter her marriege they started to\ngether a new home on the old Lee\nfarm near Seville.\nTo this union were born four child\nren; Clara, who died in infancy; El\nmer Everett, who now lives on the\nold farm; William Beecher, who re\nsides in Wadsworth, and Katie who\ndied May 19, 1917. The husband and\nfather died on March 18 of this pres\nent year. There remain to mourn the\nloss of the departed, the two sons and\ntheir Wives; one sister, Mrs. Elizabeth\nBaker of Wadsworth. one half broth-\ner, Aaron Koppes, residing near Se\nville; two half sisters, Mrs. W. H.\ni Baker of Wadsworth and Miss Sarah\nI Koppes, the latter having been a mem\nI bar of the Lee home for fourteen\nyears, besides a host of friends.\nMrs. Lee was a member of the\nMethodist church at Seville, and al\nthough unable to attend in recent\nyears, her interest and support were\nnever lacking. Her ambition in life\nas well as that of the husband and\nfather was the home idealone\nwhich was not only conducive to all\nthat was great and good in life, but\none which always carried ahearty\nwelcome and a tender ministry to all\nwho might enter therein. i\nffff\n8\n1\n1921 The dawn of better days the be\nginning of better times for all people.\nMay the new year bring you sunshine\nand happiness, a return of prosperity T\nFor the favors accorded us in the stren\nuous year just ended, our grateful thanks\nfor the year commencing, a practical demon\nstration of our appreciation of your valued\npatronage. i j\n0. N. LEACH GUNKELMAN\ni\nmil\nTHE MEDINA SENTINEL AND DAILY\nPLAIN DEALER\nMR PARMER\nWe will sell Swift's Fertilizer\nDirect to s You\nour prices are guaranteed to compete\nwith all goods of the same class.\nWe have received cars of the following the last week:\nCement, Lumber and Oil Meal. After the first of the year\nthere will be a reductjon in the prices of the following:\n43 per cent Cotton Seed Meal\nOil Meal. Tile and Bran\nPlenty of Goal and Flour on hand.\nThe surest way to have a Happy New Year is to fix\nthat old fence with some of our American Field Fence.\nTHE\nELEVATOR SUPPLY CO.\nValley City, Ohio\nDAILY PLAIN DEALER\nTHE MEDINA SENTINEL\niipwiii af r i n \"in i \"i Tin i&saca&ss' giini\nmm\nDAILY PLAIN DEALER ALONE COSTS\n$5.00\nThis Offer Holds Good\nSubscribe\nftr mtifmb m VI\"\niiniiiiiii\n$5.50 PER YEAR\nYear\nUntil January 15\nNow\nm&ym mfmmy$\nJ3","height":"28124","width":"18644"}}
